author: Dave Melton
title: Whitney Siewin wins vault as Chesterton earns first sectional title since 2003
text:
Whitney Siewin wins vault as Chesterton earns first sectional title since 2003 Whitney Siewin wins vault as Chesterton earns first sectional title since 2003 Kyle Telechan / Post-Tribune Lake Central's Gabrielle DeVries performs on the balance beam during Saturday's Chesterton Sectional. Lake Central's Gabrielle DeVries performs on the balance beam during Saturday's Chesterton Sectional. (Kyle Telechan / Post-Tribune) Dave Melton Post-Tribune 
Chesterton freshman Whitney Siewin had one responsibility at Saturday's Chesterton Sectional: vault. 
All season long, she had struggled with keeping her legs straight while flipping through the air. 
"I got it once during a dual meet with Crown Point, but I didn't land it," she said. "Then I tried it at practice (Friday) night, and I got it." 
She hit it again during the sectional meet, winning the event with a 9.5 and wrapping up Chesterton's team title â€” its first since 2003. 
"She did the best vault I've ever seen from her," Chesterton coach Dawn Matthys said of Siewin. 
But Siewin was far from the only contributor to Chesterton's team score of 113.525, topping Valparaiso's second-place score of 111.5. 
Sophomore Jordan Bush had the highest score on floor (9.65), and freshman Sophie Hunzelman took care of the rest by winning beam (9.725), bars (9.65) and all-around (38.4). 
But the individual accolades were not what had Hunzelman beaming after the meet. 
"I was more excited for the team win," she said. "We've been undefeated all season, and it's just really exciting. It's been our year." 
Matthys confirmed that in spite of her team's first-place score, it was not one of the Trojans' best performances of the season. 
"It wasn't a great day for us," she said. "So it's still great to come out with a 113 on what was not our best day. It feels good. We've led all year, we've been undefeated all year and it's great to stay in that same spot." 
The closest competition came for third place in the team standings. Merrillville (110.325) finished third to earn the final team berth to the Valparaiso Regional, just ahead of Michigan City (110.15), Portage (109.3) and Crown Point (108.65). 
Merrillville senior Heather Osorio did not practice all week while nursing an injury to her right leg. But she still managed a second-place score of 9.55 on bars to help the Pirates clinch third. 
"I was pretty nervous," Osorio said while sporting a protective boot on her right leg. "Once I got through warmups, that was the most I'd done all week. It was hurting, but I couldn't stop because this was all for my team." 
Along with the top three teams, eight other gymnasts qualified for the Valparaiso Regional. 
Michigan City's Megan Gushrowski (beam), Meghan Miller (vault) and Caroline Weber (floor), Lake Central's Gabrielle DeVries (vault), Crown Point's Paige Hein (beam) and Shannon Harrison (beam, floor), LaPorte's Sarah Zygmuntowski (floor) and Portage's Michaella Drake (all-around) all advanced. 
Dave Melton is a freelance reporter for the Post-Tribune.
